# Regression guard for a SIGABRT panic that fired during a normal chat
# turn through the mock provider. Originally observed on 2026-04-23 as a
# generic "segfault on .done"; the TUI simulator pinned it to
# std.http.contentLengthStream (Zig 0.15.2) accessing
# `reader.state.body_remaining_content_length` after the reader had
# transitioned to .ready. Real providers (Anthropic, OpenAI, Ollama)
# stream chunked, so they don't trip the bug; the mock server uses
# Content-Length, which does. Fixed in src/llm/streaming.zig by
# switching readLine off readSliceShort and onto Reader.stream with a
# body_done sticky flag.
#
# What the scenario does today: drives one chat turn against the mock
# provider, then exits zag via `/quit`. A future regression of the
# contentLengthStream bug (or any other crash on the streaming-read
# path) would either re-introduce a SIGABRT before `/quit` lands (the
# harness writes crash.txt and `wait_exit` reaps the signal — exit 0
# still, but crash.txt is the tell), or the agent would never finish
# the turn and `wait_exit` would time out instead of exiting cleanly.

spawn ./zig-out/bin/zag
wait_text /Welcome to zag/
wait_idle 500ms
send "hello" <Enter>
wait_idle 5s
send "/quit" <Enter>
wait_exit
snapshot final
